%N A395413 a(n) = b(n+1)/b(n) where b is defined in the comments.
%C A395413 Let f(n) be the lcm of A005934(1)..A005934(n). Let b(n) be the n-th distinct term in the range of f.
%C A395413 Knowing terms of this sequences should ease computation of terms for A005934. For example, we can know the largest term with k distinct prime factors and so per prime factor the largest possible multiplicity which enables trimming the search.
%e A395413 A005934 starts:
%e A395413 1, 4, 8, 16, 32, 64, 128, 144, 216, 288, 432, 864, 1296, 1728, 2592, 3456, 5184, 7776, 10368, 15552, ...
%e A395413 the lcm of first n terms starts:
%e A395413 1, 4, 8, 16, 32, 64, 128, 1152, 3456, 3456, 3456, 3456, 10368, 10368, 10368, 10368, 10368, 31104, 31104, ...
%e A395413 Distinct terms are in this list are:
%e A395413 1, 4, 8, 16, 32, 64, 128, 1152, 3456, 10368, 31104, ...
%e A395413 Consecutive ratios are this sequence:
%e A395413 4, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 9, 3, 3, 3, ...
